TCGAbin(bin)pvalue

Requirement Description

Input TCGA expression matrix, calculate bin (or not take bin), batch calculate correlation coefficient and pvalue of one gene with multiple genes according to the method in the article, and draw the graph in the article.

https://www.nature.com/articles/nature13473

fromhttps://www.nature.com/articles/nature13473

/

ChIPRNA-seq

ChIP-seqATAC-seqDNAbin

Application Scenarios

Batch screen which genes are positively/negatively correlated with your gene of interest.

Not only for gene expression correlation analysis, but also for correlation analysis of transcription factor binding (ChIP) and target gene fold change (RNA-seq) as in the example. Simply replace the gene information in the example with locus information.

When plotting thousands of loci such as ChIP-seq, ATAC-seq, or DNA methylation, you can try this binning approach.

pearsonspearman

Calculate the correlation coefficient

Two methods are used here to calculate the correlation coefficient: pearson and spearman

#  / Extract expression data of target gene
# (symbol) / Get expression values of target gene from expression matrix
target.exps <- tcga_expr[symbol,]

#  / Extract expression data of other genes
#  / Remove target gene row from expression matrix
other.expr <- tcga_expr[-which(rownames(tcga_expr)==symbol),]

# Pearson / Calculate Pearson correlation
#  / Transpose matrix and calculate correlation with target gene
sgcor <- as.data.frame(cor(t(other.expr), t(target.exps))) #pearson / Default is Pearson
colnames(sgcor) <- "r_pearson"  #  / Rename column

# Pearsonp / Calculate p-values for Pearson correlation (time-consuming)
sgcor$pval_pearson <- apply(other.expr, 1, function(x) (cor.test(x, t(target.exps))$p.value))


# Spearman / Calculate Spearman correlation
sgcor_spearman <- as.data.frame(cor(t(other.expr), t(target.exps), method = "spearman"))
colnames(sgcor_spearman) <- "r_spearman"  #  / Rename column
sgcor_spearman$pval_spearman <- apply(other.expr, 1, function(x)(cor.test(x, t(target.exps), method = "spearman")$p.value))

#  / Combine both correlation results
cors <- cbind(sgcor, sgcor_spearman)
cors$gene <- rownames(other.expr)  #  / Add gene name column
head(cors)  #  / Preview results
##          r_pearson pval_pearson    r_spearman pval_spearman   gene
## TMSB10  0.09867739  0.012231174  0.1383104698  0.0004314835 TMSB10
## ACTB   -0.05030063  0.202375044  0.0003180122  0.9935734543   ACTB
## FTL     0.06542165  0.097162665  0.0138442443  0.7258420838    FTL
## S100A6  0.10674522  0.006700422  0.1200420713  0.0022773974 S100A6
## RPS18  -0.02431332  0.537963688 -0.0290373720  0.4619684144  RPS18
## LCN2    0.01620266  0.681508532  0.1145477462  0.0036046425   LCN2
# NA / Filter valid results (remove NAs)
newcor <- cors[!(is.na(cors$r_pearson)),]
dim(newcor)  #  / Check remaining gene count
## [1] 999   5
# Pearson / Sort by Pearson correlation coefficient
sortcor <- newcor[order(newcor$r_pearson, newcor$r_spearman, decreasing = T),]

# Top / Extract top correlated genes
# Top6Top6 / Get top 6 positive and negative correlated genes
topcor <- sortcor[c(1:topnumber, #Top 6 / Top 6 positive
                   (nrow(sortcor) - topnumber + 1):nrow(sortcor)),] #Top 6 / Top 6 negative
rownames(topcor)  # Top / Show top gene names
##  [1] "EIF3I"   "PRDX1"   "KHDRBS1" "UQCRH"   "HMGN2"   "MAGOH"   "SPARC"  
##  [8] "SRGN"    "COL6A2"  "TYROBP"  "LGALS1"  "IGFBP7"
#  / Prepare visualization data
genes <- c(symbol,rownames(topcor))  # Top / Combine target and top genes
genesexps <- as.data.frame(t(tcga_expr[genes,]))  #  / Transpose expression matrix
sortgenesexps <- genesexps[order(genesexps[,1]),]  #  / Sort by target gene expression
samplenum <- nrow(sortgenesexps)  #  / Get sample count

ChIP-seqpeakbin

binpointnumberNULL

The input data in the example is the peak of ChIP-seq, directly drawing even there will be tens of thousands of points, therefore, the author took bin.

Instead of taking bin, you can also draw all the points, and set pointnumber to NULL in the parameter settings.

#  / Set number of points for plotting
# pointnumber / If pointnumber is NULL, use all samples
if(is.null(pointnumber)){
  pointnumber = samplenum
}

#  / Group samples into equally sized bins
#  / Create grouping factor variable
group <- as.integer(cut(1:samplenum, 
                       breaks = c(seq(from = 0.5, to = samplenum, 
                                     by = samplenum/pointnumber), 
                                 samplenum + 0.5)))

#  / Initialize dataframe for storing results
ddf <- data.frame(row.names = 1:pointnumber)

#  / Calculate median expression for each gene in each bin
for(i in 1:(1 + topnumber*2)){  # top / Loop through target and top genes
  ddf <- cbind(ddf, tapply(sortgenesexps[,i], group, median))
}

#  / Set column names
colnames(ddf) <- c(symbol, topcor$gene)

# ggplot / Melt data to long format for ggplot
mddf <- melt(ddf, id.vars = symbol)

# p / Add correlation coefficients and p-values
# Pearson / Using Pearson correlation results
# Spearmanr_spearmanpval_spearman / For Spearman, replace with r_spearman and pval_spearman
mddf$r <- topcor[mddf$variable, ]$r_pearson
mddf$P <- topcor[mddf$variable, ]$pval_pearson

EIF3I

Start drawing

One gene at a time

Take EIF3I for example.

#  / Select data for specific gene
friend <- "EIF3I"  #  / Set gene to analyze
df <- mddf[mddf$variable == friend,]  #  / Filter data for this gene

# r / Format correlation coefficient r display
# r / Create expression with italic r and value
rvalue <- as.character(as.expression(substitute(~~italic(r)~"="~rvalue, list(rvalue = format(round(unique(df$r),2), nsmall= 2)))))

# p / Format p-value display
# P / Create expression with italic P and scientific notation
pvalue <- as.character(as.expression(substitute(~~italic(P)~"="~pvalue, list(pvalue = format(sprintf("%1.1e", unique(df$P)), nsmall= 2)))))

#  / Create scatter plot
ggplot(df, aes_string(x = symbol, y = "value")) +
  geom_point() +  #  / Add points
  ylab(friend) +  # y / Set y-axis label as gene name
  theme_classic() +  #  / Use classic theme
  
  #  / Add statistical annotations
  # x,y / Need to adjust x,y positions based on data range
  annotate("text", x = 334, y = 350, label = rvalue, parse = TRUE) +  # r / Add r value
  annotate("text", x = 340, y = 300, label = pvalue, parse = TRUE) +  # p / Add p value
  
  #  / Add linear regression line
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE, colour = "#206BB5")  #  / Blue regression line

Batch drawing

# dlplyggplot
# Split data by gene using dlply and create multiple ggplot objects
# mddfvariable()
# Group mddf dataframe by variable (gene name), create scatter plot for each gene
plist <- dlply(mddf, .(variable), function(trig) {
  ggplot(trig, aes_string(x = symbol, y = "value")) +
    geom_point() +  #  / Add scatter points
    ylab(unique(trig$variable)) +  # y / Set y-axis label to current gene name
    theme_classic() +  #  / Use clean classic theme
    
    # p
    # Add title showing correlation coefficient and p-value
    ggtitle(paste0("r = ", round(unique(trig$r), 2),  # r2 / Show r rounded to 2 decimal places
            "\nP = ", sprintf("%1.1e", unique(trig$P)))) +  # p / Show p-value in scientific notation
    
    # ()
    # Add linear regression line (blue, no confidence interval)
    geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE, colour = "#206BB5")
})

# cowplotplot_grid
# Arrange all plots into grid using plot_grid from cowplot package
pg <- plot_grid(
  plotlist = plist,  #  / List of plots
  ncol = 3,  # 3 / 3 plots per row
  align = "hv"  #  / Align horizontally and vertically
)
